<li id="cite_note-yeziditruth_sheik-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-yeziditruth_sheik_8-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_reformer_sheikh_adi" class="external text" title="http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_reformer_sheikh_adi" rel="nofollow">"Yezidi Reformer: Sheikh Adi"</a>. <i>The Truth about the Yezidis</i>. YezidiTruth.org, A Humanitarian Organization, Sedona, AZ<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_reformer_sheikh_adi" class="external free" title="http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_reformer_sheikh_adi" rel="nofollow">http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_reformer_sheikh_adi</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Yezidi+Reformer%3A+Sheikh+Adi&amp;rft.atitle=The+Truth+about+the+Yezidis&amp;rft.pub=YezidiTruth.org%2C+A+Humanitarian+Organization%2C+Sedona%2C+AZ&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.yeziditruth.org%2Fyezidi_reformer_sheikh_adi&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Yazidi"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-yeziditruth_religious-9">^ <a href="#cite_ref-yeziditruth_religious_9-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-yeziditruth_religious_9-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-yeziditruth_religious_9-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-yeziditruth_religious_9-3" title=""><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_religious_tradition" class="external text" title="http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_religious_tradition" rel="nofollow">"Yezidi Religious Tradition"</a>. <i>The Truth about the Yezidis</i>. YezidiTruth.org, A Humanitarian Organization, Sedona, AZ<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_religious_tradition" class="external free" title="http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_religious_tradition" rel="nofollow">http://www.yeziditruth.org/yezidi_religious_tradition</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Yezidi+Religious+Tradition&amp;rft.atitle=The+Truth+about+the+Yezidis&amp;rft.pub=YezidiTruth.org%2C+A+Humanitarian+Organization%2C+Sedona%2C+AZ&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.yeziditruth.org%2Fyezidi_religious_tradition&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Yazidi"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="news" id="CITEREFMacFarquhar2003"><a href="/wiki/Neil_MacFarquhar" title="Neil MacFarquhar">MacFarquhar, Neill</a> (2003-01-03). "<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E5DF1E3FF930A35752C0A9659C8B63&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all" class="external text" title="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E5DF1E3FF930A35752C0A9659C8B63&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all" rel="nofollow">Bashiqa Journal: A Sect Shuns Lettuce and Gives the Devil His Due</a>". <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">The New York Times</a></i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E5DF1E3FF930A35752C0A9659C8B63&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all" class="external free" title="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E5DF1E3FF930A35752C0A9659C8B63&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all" rel="nofollow">http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E5DF1E3FF930A35752C0A9659C8B63&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-03-31</span>.  "Yazidis pray three times a day, at dawn, midday and sunset, facing the direction of the sun each time. 'The sun is very holy to us,' said Walid Abu Khudur, the stocky, bearded guardian of the temple built in honor of a holy man here. 'It is like the eye of God, so we pray toward it.'... They have adopted Christian rituals like baptism and a smattering of practices from Islam ranging from circumcision to removal of their shoes inside their temples. The importance of fire as a divine manifestation comes from Zoroastrianism, the ancient Persian faith that forms the core of Yazidi beliefs. Indeed their very name is likely taken from an old Persian word for angel."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Bashiqa+Journal%3A+A+Sect+Shuns+Lettuce+and+Gives+the+Devil+His+Due&amp;rft.jtitle=%5B%5BThe+New+York+Times%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=MacFarquhar&amp;rft.aufirst=Neill&amp;rft.au=MacFarquhar%2C+Neill&amp;rft.date=2003-01-03&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fgst%2Ffullpage.html%3Fres%3D9B00E5DF1E3FF930A35752C0A9659C8B63%26sec%3D%26spon%3D%26pagewanted%3Dall&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Yazidi"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="news" id="CITEREFHedges1993"><a href="/wiki/Chris_Hedges" title="Chris Hedges">Hedges, Chris</a> (1993-05-31). "<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE5DA133FF932A05756C0A965958260&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all" class="external text" title="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE5DA133FF932A05756C0A965958260&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all" rel="nofollow">Sheik Adi Journal: Satan's Alive and Well, but the Sect May Be Dying</a>". <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">The New York Times</a></i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE5DA133FF932A05756C0A965958260&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all" class="external free" title="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE5DA133FF932A05756C0A965958260&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all" rel="nofollow">http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE5DA133FF932A05756C0A965958260&amp;sec=&amp;spon=&amp;pagewanted=all</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-07-21</span>.  "The Yazidis, who are part of Iraq's Kurdish minority, had 100 of 150 villages demolished during the counterinsurgency operation against the Kurdish rebel movement that reached its peak in 1988. The campaign, which moved hundreds of thousands of people to collective villages, saw 4,000 Kurdish villages dynamited into rubble... The sect follows the teachings of Sheik Adi, a holy man who died in 1162, and whose crypt lies in the shrine in the Lalish Valley, about 15 miles east of Mosul. The shrine's graceful, fluted spires poke above the trees and dominate the fertile valley... Like Zoroastrians they venerate fire, the sun and the mulberry tree. They believe in the transmigration of souls, often into animals. The sect does not accept converts and banishes anyone who marries outside the faith. Yazidis are forbidden to disclose most of their rituals and beliefs to nonbelievers."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Sheik+Adi+Journal%3A+Satan%27s+Alive+and+Well%2C+but+the+Sect+May+Be+Dying&amp;rft.jtitle=%5B%5BThe+New+York+Times%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=Hedges&amp;rft.aufirst=Chris&amp;rft.au=Hedges%2C+Chris&amp;rft.date=1993-05-31&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fgst%2Ffullpage.html%3Fres%3D9F0CE5DA133FF932A05756C0A965958260%26sec%3D%26spon%3D%26pagewanted%3Dall&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Yazidi"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-GUARDIAN-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-GUARDIAN_12-0" title="">^</a></b> Lattimer, Mark (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2007-12-13"><a href="/wiki/2007" title="2007">2007</a>-<a href="/wiki/December_13" title="December 13">12-13</a></span>) "<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2007/dec/13/gender.iraq" class="external text" title="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2007/dec/13/gender.iraq" rel="nofollow">Freedom Lost</a>," <i><a href="/wiki/The_Guardian" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</a></i>, <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>.</li>
